---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const title = 'Typhoon Bifurcation: two PRC pillars, one strategic window';
const date = '2026-05-26';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <p class="kicker">Sunday Brief · {date}</p>
  <h1>{title}</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Volt Typhoon and Salt Typhoon are the same service running two
    different doctrinal mandates against the same victim country. The
    bifurcation matters — and it's been hiding in plain sight.
  </p>

  <h2>The setup</h2>

  <p>
    The Microsoft "weather" taxonomy gave us a curiously parallel pair
    of names in 2023 and 2024: <a href="/actor/cn/mss/volt-typhoon">Volt
    Typhoon</a> and <a href="/actor/cn/mss/salt-typhoon">Salt Typhoon</a>.
    Both attributed by US government and tier-one vendors to PRC
    services. Both targeting US critical infrastructure. Both
    persistent, careful, living-off-the-land. The temptation in early
    reporting was to fold them together: "PRC pre-positioning in
    critical infrastructure."
  </p>
  <p>
    That collapse loses what AUSPEX is built to surface: the two
    clusters are running <em>different doctrinal mandates</em>, and
    the difference is operationally and analytically load-bearing.
  </p>

  <h2>Volt — coercive pre-positioning</h2>

  <p>
    The <a href="/event/2023-05/volt-typhoon-public-disclosure">May 2023
    Five Eyes joint disclosure (CISA AA23-144A)</a> framed Volt
    Typhoon's intrusions in US energy, water, communications, and
    transportation as <em>pre-positioning</em> — establishing access
    that would be useful to disrupt rather than to collect from. FBI
    Director Christopher Wray's testimony to the House Select Committee
    on the CCP, 2024-01-31, named the doctrinal motivation explicitly:
    the intent is to "wreak havoc and cause real-world harm to American
    citizens and communities" in the event of a Taiwan-related conflict.
  </p>
  <p>
    That's an <em>attested</em> doctrine link in the AUSPEX sense —
    the attributing US-government source named the strategic goal in
    plain language. The event maps to the
    <a href="/doctrine/cn/taiwan-reunification">Taiwan Reunification
    doctrine</a>, specifically the coercive-options-pre-positioning
    pillar. Subsidiary linkage to
    <a href="/doctrine/cn/mcf">Military-Civil Fusion</a>'s
    civilian-infrastructure-targeting pillar is <em>strongly inferred</em>
    rather than attested — the target mix is consistent with PLA
    strategic writing on coercive leverage, but no Chinese-source text
    attests to the specific mandate.
  </p>

  <h2>Salt — telecom intelligence collection</h2>

  <p>
    <a href="/event/2024-09/salt-typhoon-us-telecom-compromise">Salt
    Typhoon's compromise of US major telecoms (Verizon, AT&amp;T,
    Lumen, T-Mobile)</a>, disclosed beginning September 2024 and
    formalized in the
    <a href="/event/2025-08/cisa-aa25-239a-salt-typhoon-advisory">August
    2025 Five Eyes joint advisory AA25-239A</a>, is a
    <em>different</em> mandate. The targeting is the carrier-grade
    backbone: lawful-intercept systems (CALEA), call-detail-records,
    metadata, the means by which the US government conducts its own
    surveillance of foreign targets and the metadata trail of US
    political figures.
  </p>
  <p>
    Salt Typhoon's mandate, as articulated in the AA25-239A
    documentation and corroborated by the January 2025 Treasury SDN
    designations against Sichuan Juxinhe Network Technology, is
    strategic intelligence collection — counter-intelligence against
    US lawful-intercept and political-leadership communications. That
    aligns to the
    <a href="/doctrine/cn/national-intelligence-law-2017">2017 National
    Intelligence Law</a>'s state-collection mandate, not to
    Taiwan-pre-positioning. There is no plausible Taiwan-conflict use
    case for CALEA targeting; there is a strong Five-Year-Plan-aligned
    case for it as state intelligence-collection support.
  </p>

  <h2>Why the bifurcation matters</h2>

  <p>
    When the two clusters get collapsed into "PRC critical-infrastructure
    targeting," three things go wrong:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Defensive prioritization gets muddled.</strong> An
      energy-utility CISO and a Tier-1 telecom CISO face <em>different</em>
      adversaries with different tradecraft and different windows of
      consequence. Conflating them produces a generic threat picture
      that fits neither.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Policy responses get miscalibrated.</strong> Volt is a
      deterrence problem — what makes the Davidson Window less
      attractive? Salt is a counter-intelligence problem — what makes
      US lawful-intercept architecture less exploitable? The instrument
      mix differs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Attribution drift gets papered over.</strong> The
      Microsoft Silk Typhoon / Hafnium / APT27 cluster reconciliation
      is already a contested mess (AUSPEX flags this on the
      <a href="/event/2024-12/treasury-beyondtrust-silk-typhoon">December
      2024 BeyondTrust event</a>). Folding Salt into Volt or vice
      versa adds another layer of cluster-collapse that will need to
      be unwound later.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The MSS as a multi-mandate service</h2>

  <p>
    The deeper analytic point is that the
    <a href="/service/cn/mss">Ministry of State Security</a> is not a
    single-mandate service. It runs simultaneously:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Industrial-collection mandates aligned to
      <a href="/doctrine/cn/mic2025">MIC2025</a> (APT10, APT31, APT41
      indictments).</li>
    <li>Taiwan-coercion mandates (Volt Typhoon).</li>
    <li>Strategic intelligence-collection mandates (Salt Typhoon,
      Hafnium 2021 Exchange campaign).</li>
    <li>Counter-intelligence on diaspora dissidents.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These mandates are partially provincial-bureau-segmented (Hainan,
    Tianjin, Shanghai, Guangdong SSBs have distinct portfolios per
    DOJ indictments and the i-SOON leak corpus), but they are <em>not</em>
    cleanly separable by actor cluster. Volt and Salt are best read as
    <em>distinct mandate streams</em> rather than as distinct units.
  </p>

  <h2>What we're watching</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      The 2027 Davidson Window. Volt Typhoon's persistence and
      patience are calibrated against it. Telegraphed disclosures
      between now and then will tell us whether the access has been
      preserved or burned.
    </li>
    <li>
      Salt Typhoon's reach into allied (non-US) Five-Eyes telecom
      backbones. AA25-239A hinted at scope beyond the US; the next
      shoe will likely be a UK NCSC or CCCS-led disclosure.
    </li>
    <li>
      Whether the
      <a href="/doctrine/cn/national-intelligence-law-2017">2017 NIL</a>
      mandate visibly broadens into financial-services targeting.
      That would be a meaningful pillar expansion.
    </li>
  </ul>

